, width 
<quantity box="[1060,1164,151,177]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.8999999999999995" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="0.69">0.69 mm</quantity>
. Tergite 1 (IV) in dorsal view longer than tergites 2–4 (V–VII) combined, setose basal sulcus separated by mediobasal and one pair of transverse basolateral sockets, with pair of thick discal carinae; tergites 2 and 3 (V and VI) lacking foveae, 4 (VII) as long as 2 and 3 combined along middle, with one pair of basolateral foveae, 2–4 each with pair of thin lateral carinae, tergite 5 (VIII) semicircular, posterior margin roundly emarginate at middle. Sternite 2 (IV) with large mediobasal and broad basolateral sockets, with pair of long, thick lateral carinae; midlength of sternite 2 (IV) as long as sternites 3–5 (V–VII) combined, 3 and 4 short, 5 slightly longer than 4, 3–5 lacking foveae, sternite 6 (VIII) transverse, posterior margin emarginate at middle, sternite 7 (IX) (
<figureCitation box="[758,855,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="45.[151,250,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,562,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-165@45.[151,1436,561,1789]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 18. Morphology of Arthromelodes lebus sp. nov., male. A. Dorsal habitus. B. Head and pronotum. C. Antennomeres 7–11. D. Mesotibia. E. Sternite 7 (IX). F, G. Aedeagus, lateral (F) and ventral (G). Scale bars: 0.5 mm in A; 0.3 mm in B; 0.2 mm in C, D; 0.05 mm in E; 0.1 mm in F, G." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6340774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6340774/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Fig. 18E</figureCitation>
) slightly oval, moderately sclerotized, apex rounded and with few long setae along apical margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,151,934]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[325,452,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="45.[151,250,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,562,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-165@45.[151,1436,561,1789]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 18. Morphology of Arthromelodes lebus sp. nov., male. A. Dorsal habitus. B. Head and pronotum. C. Antennomeres 7–11. D. Mesotibia. E. Sternite 7 (IX). F, G. Aedeagus, lateral (F) and ventral (G). Scale bars: 0.5 mm in A; 0.3 mm in B; 0.2 mm in C, D; 0.05 mm in E; 0.1 mm in F, G." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6340774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6340774/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Fig. 18F, G</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[468,567,475,501]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="0.28">0.28 mm</quantity>
long, strongly asymmetric; median lobe with large basal capsule and rounded triangular foramen, ventral stalk in lateral view broad along basal 2/3 and narrowing apically; dorsal lobe elongate, broadest near middle, with pointed apex; parameres reduced to single broad membranous structure.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,151,934]" box="[199,415,583,609]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis box="[199,283,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Female</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,151,934]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,434,618,645]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
The new species is allied with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2022" box="[798,968,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Arthromelodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassicornis">
<emphasis box="[798,815,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[831,968,619,644]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">crassicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the similar modifications of antennomeres 9 and 10, setose metaventrite, and general form of the aedeagus. These two species can be readily separated by the lack of a median longitudinal sulcus of the vertex, the strongly enlarged antennomeres 7, and a much stouter form of the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2022" box="[431,522,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Arthromelodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lebus">
<emphasis box="[431,448,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[463,522,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">lebus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The setose metaventrite is also shared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2022" box="[1035,1205,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Arthromelodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepaeformis">
<emphasis box="[1035,1052,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1067,1205,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">nepaeformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the male of the latter species possesses strongly sinuate protibiae and modified protarsomeres 1, which are characteristic for that species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
